<!--
VOICING PLAN — Now Praise We Christ, the Holy One (C major, 4/4):

This hymn has a modal character, dwelling heavily on ii (Dm) and vi (Am) harmonies
before arriving at I (C). The final bar's E annotation (E major) is likely a Picardy
third (or borrowed III) ending on E — the diatonic harp plays Em (iii) underneath.

Phrase 1 (mm. 1–4): The hymn opens with an immediate Dm (ii) whole step down from C.
The arrangement opens with a 2-beat ii voicing, making the hymn feel slightly modal
(Dorian on D). Beat-by-beat chord changes in M2 (ii→V→iii→ii) provide inner motion.
M3's rest on beat 3 creates a textural breath — both harp staves rest, letting the
melody breathe. The pickup note D on beat 4 of M3 sets up the next phrase.

Phrase 2 (mm. 5–8): M5's stepwise ascent A→B→C (ii→V→I) is the most tonal moment
of the piece. The arrangement voices this as a clear diatonic ii→V→I progression with
the LH bass stepping D→G→C. M6 opens with a deliberate rest on beat 1 (matching the
melody's rest), then flows into vi7→IV→I.

Non-diatonic G# (M7 beat 4): The melody has a G# (from "^E" annotation = E major
context). Since G# is chromatic in C, the harp plays G natural (diatonic) underneath,
using Em (iii) voicings. The melody's G# passes against the harp's G natural —
a mild dissonance that resolves on the next beat.

Phrase 3 (mm. 9–11): The F→Dm→C→F rocking motion in M9 is supported by IV "334"
and ii "334" alternating — fuller voicings for the penultimate phrase. M10 descends
iii→ii→I (E→D→C) leading to the final whole-bar E. The final chord (Em in harp
against E in melody) creates a slightly open, modal cadence appropriate for the style.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- The predominance of ii (Dm) throughout suggests Dorian modal color — the harp
  reinforces this by treating Dm as the tonal center rather than C in many phrases.
- M2 (ii→V→iii→ii): Bass steps D→G→E→D — contrary motion to the melody's A→D→G→F.
- M7→M8: I→V→vi→iii (C→G→Am→Em) is a descending-5th cycle in the inner voices,
  giving harmonic momentum to the descending melodic line C→B→A→G#.
- M10 final cadence (iii→ii→I): Bass steps E→D→C — clean stepwise bass line into
  the final E chord (iii in harp, III in the source).

TEXTURE ARC:
- Opens sparse (mm. 1–3): Half-note voicings, rests, emphasizing the modal opening.
- Builds (mm. 4–7): Quarter-note harmonic rhythm with 3–4 note LH chords.
- Climax (M9): Four distinct chords per bar, IV "334" voicings for maximum weight.
- Close (M10–11): Descends to final Em whole note. Full 3-note RH + 4-note LH for
  the closing chord, making it the densest and most sonorous moment.
-->
